  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>From 1 August 2025, Queensland has a formal vendor statement system. Under the <em>Property Law Act 2023</em>, sellers must give the buyer a Form 2 Mandatory Seller Disclosure Statement, together with a set of prescribed certificates, before the buyer signs the contract. This brings Queensland into line with the disclosure regimes that apply in Victoria (Section 32) and South Australia (Form 1), and changes a long-standing position. Authoritative guidance on the new regime is published by the <a href="https://www.qld.gov.au/law/housing-and-neighbours/buying-and-selling-a-property/seller-disclosure-statement" style="color:#6b4610;">Queensland Government</a> and the <a href="https://www.reiq.com/articles/property-law-act-2023-seller-disclosure" style="color:#6b4610;">REIQ</a>. For a step-by-step preparation guide, see our <a href="/insights/complete-seller-disclosure-checklist-queensland" style="color:#6b4610;">complete seller disclosure checklist</a>.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the Form 2 and the REIQ contract require</h2>
      <p>The Form 2 captures statutory matters such as title particulars, body corporate information for community titles lots, encumbrances and statutory notices affecting the land, zoning and overlays, contamination registrations, transport infrastructure proposals, pool safety status, and tree disputes. If the disclosure is materially incorrect or incomplete and the buyer was not aware of the true position, the buyer can terminate the contract before settlement.</p>

      <p>The standard REIQ contract of sale includes a seller's warranties section in which the seller makes representations about certain aspects of the property. These include: whether the property is subject to any encumbrances not disclosed in the contract (mortgages, easements, covenants, caveats); whether the property is part of a community title scheme and, if so, whether the body corporate disclosure statement has been provided; whether there is a pool on the property and whether a valid pool safety certificate is in place; whether all dwellings on the property have compliant smoke alarms; and whether the seller is aware of any notice, order, proposal, or requirement that has been or may be issued by a local or government authority that has not been disclosed.</p>

      <p>These warranties are not optional. If a seller signs a contract and one of the warranted items is incorrect, the buyer may have grounds to terminate the contract or seek damages, depending on the nature of the breach and when it comes to light. Getting these right before you sign requires a conversation with your solicitor, not just a quick read of the contract.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Caveat emptor: where it still has bite</h2>
      <p>Queensland property law historically gave considerable weight to caveat emptor, or buyer beware. The Property Law Act 2023 has now put a clear statutory disclosure obligation in front of the contract, so the regime sits between Victoria's full vendor statement and the older Queensland position. A buyer is still expected to conduct their own investigations into the physical condition of the property: building and pest inspections, finance, body corporate searches, and so on. The seller is not required to volunteer everything they know about the building, but they cannot misrepresent or conceal a material fact.</p>

      <p>If a seller knows about a significant defect, a dispute, a past issue, or a characteristic of the property that a buyer would consider material to their decision and conceals or misrepresents it, that conduct can constitute misleading or deceptive conduct under the Australian Consumer Law. The line between what you are required to disclose under the Form 2 and what you are entitled to leave to the buyer's own inquiries is not always obvious, which is why working with a solicitor who understands the new regime is essential.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Material facts: the disclosure obligation you cannot ignore</h2>
      <p>Even outside the formal contract warranties, Queensland sellers have an obligation under the Property Occupations Act 2014 not to misrepresent or conceal a material fact about the property. A material fact is one that would, if known, be likely to affect a buyer's decision to buy or the price they would be willing to pay.</p>

      <p>What constitutes a material fact depends on the circumstances. Known structural defects, previous flooding, undisclosed alterations made without building approval, a history of significant disputes with neighbours, or contamination issues on or near the land could all be material facts depending on the property and the buyer. You are not required to speculate about every theoretical concern, but if you are aware of something that a reasonable buyer would want to know, the safer course is to disclose it through your solicitor rather than stay silent and risk a claim after settlement.</p>

      <p>This is not just a legal risk issue: it is also a practical one. Buyers who discover something significant after settlement that they believe the seller knew about are often more determined to pursue a claim than buyers who were informed of the issue upfront. Proactive disclosure, managed properly through your solicitor, is nearly always the better outcome for both parties.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Consequences of non-disclosure</h2>
      <p>If a seller fails to disclose a material fact or provides incorrect information in the contract warranties, the consequences can range from significant to severe depending on the circumstances. A buyer who discovers a non-disclosure before settlement may be entitled to terminate the contract and recover their deposit. A buyer who discovers it after settlement may be entitled to seek damages, which could include the cost of rectifying the issue, loss of value, and in some cases, consequential losses.</p>

      <p>If the non-disclosure amounts to misleading or deceptive conduct under the Australian Consumer Law, the consequences can extend beyond contract damages to penalties and orders that go further than simple rescission. Queensland courts and tribunals have taken a firm line on deliberate non-disclosures in property transactions, and the risk of a dispute that takes years and significant legal cost to resolve is very real.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Working with your solicitor to get disclosure right</h2>
      <p>The practical approach to disclosure is to work through the contract with your solicitor before it is signed, rather than after. Your solicitor can help you identify what the contract warranties require, whether there are any issues that need to be disclosed or excluded from the warranty, and how to structure the contract to accurately reflect the property's known condition and attributes.</p>

      <p>It is also worth reviewing any documentation you have about the property before you start the process: council rates notices, building approval records, body corporate records, flood or contamination search results, and any correspondence from government authorities about the land or adjoining properties. Bringing these together before your solicitor drafts the contract gives them what they need to advise you properly.</p>

      <p>One point that often surprises sellers: over-disclosing is also a risk, though a less serious one. Volunteering information that is not material, not accurate, or that creates unnecessary uncertainty can complicate negotiations and slow the sale. Your solicitor's role is to help you disclose what needs to be disclosed, in the right way, without creating problems that did not previously exist.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common issues in Brisbane's inner east</h2>
      <p>In Brisbane's inner east, certain disclosure issues come up more frequently than others because of the age and character of the housing stock and the specific planning and environmental overlays that apply in many suburbs.</p>

      <p>Flood overlays affect a significant proportion of properties in suburbs close to the Brisbane River and Bulimba Creek catchments, including parts of Hawthorne, Bulimba, Morningside, and Norman Park. If a property is within a flood overlay or has a history of inundation, this is material information that must be reflected accurately in the contract and disclosed to buyers who ask. Council flood certificates and property reports can be obtained to document the property's flood status.</p>

      <p>Heritage listings and local heritage place designations affect many older Queenslander properties in the inner east. These impose restrictions on what can be altered or demolished, which is material to buyers who may be planning renovations. The contract should correctly reflect whether the property is listed and what that means.</p>

      <p>Easements for services, drainage, or access across inner-east properties are common, particularly in established suburbs with older infrastructure. These must be disclosed as encumbrances in the contract and may affect how the land can be used or developed. A title search prior to contract preparation will identify any registered easements.</p>

